# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: rails-deep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] This guide is an introduction to Active Record.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] Active Record is part of the M in MVC - the model - which is the layer of the system responsible for representing data and business logic.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] Active Record helps you create and use Ruby objects whose attributes require persistent storage to a database.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] What is the difference between Active Record and Active Model?
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] It's possible to model data with Ruby objects that do *not* need to be backed by a database.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] Active Model is commonly used for that in Rails, making Active Record and Active Model both part of the M in MVC, as well as your own plain Ruby objects.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] The term "Active Record" also refers to a software architecture pattern.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] Active Record in Rails is an implementation of that pattern.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] It's also a description of something called an Object Relational Mapping system.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] The Active Record pattern is described by Martin Fowler in the book *Patterns of Enterprise Application Architecture* as "an object that wraps a row in a database table, encapsulates the database access, and adds domain logic to that data." Active Record objects carry both data and behavior.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] Active Record classes match very closely to the record structure of the underlying database.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] This way users can easily read from and write to the database, as you will see in the examples below.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] Object Relational Mapping, commonly referred to as ORM, is a technique that connects the rich objects of a programming language to tables in a relational database management system (RDBMS).
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] In the case of a Rails application, these are Ruby objects.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] Using an ORM, the attributes of Ruby objects, as well as the relationship between objects, can be easily stored and retrieved from a database without writing SQL statements directly.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] Overall, ORMs minimize the amount of database access code you have to write.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] Basic knowledge of relational database management systems (RDBMS) and structured query language (SQL) is helpful in order to fully understand Active Record.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] Please refer to this SQL tutorial (or this RDBMS tutorial) or study them by other means if you would like to learn more.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] When writing applications using other programming languages or frameworks, it may be necessary to write a lot of configuration code.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] This is particularly true for ORM frameworks in general.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] However, if you follow the conventions adopted by Rails, you'll write very little to no configuration code when creating Active Record models.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] Rails adopts the idea that if you configure your applications in the same way most of the time, then that way should be the default.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] Explicit configuration should be needed only in those cases where you can't follow the convention.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] To take advantage of convention over configuration in Active Record, there are some naming and schema conventions to follow.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] And in case you need to, it is possible to override naming conventions.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] Rails will pluralize your model's class names to find the respective database table.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] For example, a class named `Book` maps to a database table named `books`.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] The Rails pluralization mechanisms are very powerful and capable of pluralizing (and singularizing) both regular and irregular words in the English language.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] This uses the Active Support pluralize method.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] For class names composed of two or more words, the model class name will follow the Ruby conventions of using an UpperCamelCase name.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] The database table name, in that case, will be a snake_case name.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] Active Record uses conventions for column names in the database tables as well, depending on the purpose of these columns.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] While these column names are optional, they are reserved by Active Record.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] Steer clear of reserved keywords when naming your table's columns.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] For example, `type` is a reserved keyword used to designate a table using Single Table Inheritance (STI).
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] If you are not using STI, use a different word to accurately describe the data you are modeling.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] When generating a Rails application, an abstract `ApplicationRecord` class will be created in `app/models/application_record.rb`.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] The `ApplicationRecord` class inherits from `ActiveRecord::Base` and it's what turns a regular Ruby class into an Active Record model.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] `ApplicationRecord` is the base class for all Active Record models in your app.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] This will create a `Book` model, mapped to a `books` table in the database, where each column in the table is mapped to attributes of the `Book` class.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] An instance of `Book` can represent a row in the `books` table.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] However, that is not how you do it normally in Rails.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] Database tables in Rails are typically created using Active Record Migrations and not raw SQL.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] If you don't specify a type for a field (e.g., `title` instead of `title:string`), Rails will default to type `string`.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] That migration creates columns `id`, `title`, `author`, `created_at` and `updated_at`.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] Each row of this table can be represented by an instance of the `Book` class with the same attributes: `id`, `title`, `author`, `created_at`, and `updated_at`.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] You can generate the Active Record model class as well as a matching migration with the command `bin/rails generate model Book title:string author:string`.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] This creates the files `app/models/book.rb`, `db/migrate/20240220143807_create_books.rb`, and a couple others for testing purposes.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] Active Record models are placed under the `app/models` directory by default.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] But you may want to organize your models by placing similar models under their own folder and namespace.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] For example, `order.rb` and `review.rb` under `app/models/book` with `Book::Order` and `Book::Review` class names, respectively.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] You can create namespaced models with Active Record.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] Setting the table_name_prefix in `Book` will allow `Order` model's database table to be named `book_orders`, instead of plain `orders`.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] The other possibility is that you already have a `Book` model that you want to keep in `app/models`.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] In that case, you can choose `n` to not overwrite `book.rb` during the `generate` command.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] What if you need to follow a different naming convention or need to use your Rails application with a legacy database?
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] No problem, you can easily override the default conventions.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] Since `ApplicationRecord` inherits from `ActiveRecord::Base`, your application's models will have a number of helpful methods available to them.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] CRUD is an acronym for the four verbs we use to operate on data: **C**reate, **R**ead, **U**pdate, and **D**elete.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] Active Record automatically creates methods to allow you to read and manipulate data stored in your application's database tables.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] Active Record makes it seamless to perform CRUD operations by using these high-level methods that abstract away database access details.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] Note that all of these convenient methods result in SQL statement(s) that are executed against the underlying database.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] The examples below show a few of the CRUD methods as well as the resulting SQL statements.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] Active Record objects can be created from a hash, a block, or have their attributes manually set after creation.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] The `new` method will return a new, non-persisted object, while `create` will save the object to the database and return it.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] Active Record provides a rich API for accessing data within a database.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] You can query a single record or multiple records, filter them by any attribute, order them, group them, select specific fields, and do anything you can do with SQL.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] We can also find specific books with `find_by` and `where`.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] There are many more Active Record methods to read and query records.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] You can learn more about them in the Active Record Query guide.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] Once an Active Record object has been retrieved, its attributes can be modified and it can be saved to the database.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] This is useful when updating several attributes at once.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] Similar to `create`, using `update` will commit the updated records to the database.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] Likewise, once retrieved, an Active Record object can be destroyed, which removes it from the database.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] Active Record allows you to validate the state of a model before it gets written into the database.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] There are several methods that allow for different types of validations.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] For example, validate that an attribute value is not empty, is unique, is not already in the database, follows a specific format, and many more.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] Methods like `save`, `create` and `update` validate a model before persisting it to the database.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] If the model is invalid, no database operations are performed.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] In this case the `save` and `update` methods return `false`.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] The `create` method still returns the object, which can be checked for errors.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] All of these methods have a bang counterpart (that is, `save!`, `create!` and `update!`), which are stricter in that they raise an `ActiveRecord::RecordInvalid` exception when validation fails.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] The `create` method always returns the model, regardless of its validity.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] You can then inspect this model for any errors.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] You can learn more about validations in the Active Record Validations guide.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] Active Record callbacks allow you to attach code to certain events in the lifecycle of your models.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] This enables you to add behavior to your models by executing code when those events occur, like when you create a new record, update it, destroy it, and so on.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] You can learn more about callbacks in the Active Record Callbacks guide.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] Rails provides a convenient way to manage changes to a database schema via migrations.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] Migrations are written in a domain-specific language and stored in files which are executed against any database that Active Record supports.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] Note that the above code is database-agnostic: it will run in MySQL, MariaDB, PostgreSQL, SQLite, and others.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] Rails keeps track of which migrations have been committed to the database and stores them in a neighboring table in that same database called `schema_migrations`.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] To run the migration and create the table, you'd run `bin/rails db:migrate`, and to roll it back and delete the table, `bin/rails db:rollback`.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] You can learn more about migrations in the Active Record Migrations guide.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] Active Record associations allow you to define relationships between models.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] Associations can be used to describe one-to-one, one-to-many, and many-to-many relationships.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] The `Author` class now has methods to add and remove books to an author, and much more.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-basics] You can learn more about associations in the Active Record Associations guide.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-pattern] In software engineering, the **active record pattern** is an architectural pattern.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-pattern] It is found in software that stores in-memory object data in relational databases.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-pattern] It was named by Martin Fowler in his 2003 book *Patterns of Enterprise Application Architecture*.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-pattern] The interface of an object conforming to this pattern would include functions such as Insert, Update, and Delete, plus properties that correspond more or less directly to the columns in the underlying database table.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-pattern] The Active Record pattern is a Data Access Layer that performs bidirectional transfer of data between a persistent data store (often a relational database) and an in-memory data representation (the domain layer).
[src:rails-deep/active-record-pattern] A database table or view is wrapped into a class.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-pattern] Thus, an object instance is tied to a single row in the table.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-pattern] After creation of an object, a new row is added to the table upon save.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-pattern] Any object loaded gets its information from the database.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-pattern] When an object is updated, the corresponding row in the table is also updated.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-pattern] The wrapper class implements accessor methods or properties for each column in the table or view.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-pattern] This pattern is commonly used by object persistence tools and in object–relational mapping (ORM).
[src:rails-deep/active-record-pattern] Typically, foreign key relationships will be exposed as an object instance of the appropriate type via a property.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-pattern] Implementations of the concept can be found in various frameworks for many programming environments.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-pattern] This will find a new `Part` object based on the first matching row from the `parts` table whose `name` column has the value "gearbox".
[src:rails-deep/active-record-pattern] Various libraries implement an active record pattern framework, such as POCO C++ Libraries in library `Poco::ActiveRecord`.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-pattern] This is a simple example of an active record object `User`, in Java.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-pattern] Here the `User` class is both the model and data access object and provides `save()`, `find()`, and `delete()` methods.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-pattern] Another critique of the active record pattern is that, due to the strong coupling of database interaction and application logic, an active record object does not follow the single responsibility principle and separation of concerns.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-pattern] This is opposed to multitier architecture, which properly addresses these practices.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-pattern] Because of this, the active record pattern is best and most often employed in simple applications that are all forms-over-data with CRUD functionality, or only as one part of an architecture.
[src:rails-deep/active-record-pattern] Typically that part is data access and why several ORMs implement the active record pattern.
[src:rails-deep/convention-over-configuration] The concept was introduced by David Heinemeier Hansson to describe the philosophy of the Ruby on Rails web framework, but is related to earlier ideas like the concept of "sensible defaults" and the principle of least astonishment in user interface design.
[src:rails-deep/convention-over-configuration] The phrase essentially means a developer only needs to specify unconventional aspects of the application.
[src:rails-deep/convention-over-configuration] For example, if there is a class Sales in the model, the corresponding table in the database is called "sales" by default.
[src:rails-deep/convention-over-configuration] It is only if one deviates from this convention, such as the table "product sales", that one needs to write code regarding these names.
[src:rails-deep/convention-over-configuration] When the convention implemented by the tool matches the desired behavior, it behaves as expected without having to write configuration files.
[src:rails-deep/convention-over-configuration] Only when the desired behavior deviates from the implemented convention is explicit configuration required.
[src:rails-deep/convention-over-configuration] Ruby on Rails' use of the phrase is particularly focused on its default project file and directory structure, which prevent developers from having to write XML configuration files to specify which modules the framework should load, which was common in many earlier frameworks.
[src:rails-deep/convention-over-configuration] Other methods of decreasing the number of decisions a developer needs to make include programming idioms and configuration libraries with a multilayered architecture.
[src:rails-deep/convention-over-configuration] Some frameworks need multiple configuration files, each with many settings.
[src:rails-deep/convention-over-configuration] These provide information specific to each project, ranging from URLs to mappings between classes and database tables.
[src:rails-deep/convention-over-configuration] Many configuration files with many parameters are often difficult to maintain.
[src:rails-deep/convention-over-configuration] For example, early versions of the Java persistence mapper Hibernate mapped entities and their fields to the database by describing these relationships in XML files.
[src:rails-deep/convention-over-configuration] Most of this information could have been revealed by conventionally mapping class names to the identically named database tables and the fields to their columns, respectively.
[src:rails-deep/convention-over-configuration] Later versions did away with the XML configuration file and instead employed these very conventions, deviations from which can be indicated through the use of Java annotations (see JavaBeans specification, linked below).
[src:rails-deep/convention-over-configuration] Many modern frameworks use a *convention over configuration* approach.
[src:rails-deep/convention-over-configuration] The concept is older, however, dating back to the concept of a default, and can be spotted more recently in the roots of Java libraries.
[src:rails-deep/convention-over-configuration] For example, the JavaBeans specification relies on it heavily.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] Traditionally used for desktop graphical user interfaces (GUIs), this pattern became popular for designing web applications.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] Popular programming languages have MVC frameworks that facilitate the implementation of the pattern.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] One of the seminal insights in the early development of graphical user interfaces, MVC became one of the first approaches to describe and implement software constructs in terms of their responsibilities.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] Trygve Reenskaug created MVC while working on Smalltalk-79 as a visiting scientist at the Xerox Palo Alto Research Center (PARC) in the late 1970s.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] He wanted a pattern that could be used to structure any program where users interact with a large, convoluted data set.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] His design initially had four parts: Model, view, thing, and editor.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] After discussing it with the other Smalltalk developers, he and the rest of the group settled on model, view, and controller instead.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] In their final design, a model represents some part of the program purely and intuitively.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] A view is a visual representation of a model, retrieving data from the model to display to the user and passing requests back and forth between the user and the model.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] A controller is an organizational part of the user interface that lays out and coordinates multiple Views on the screen, and which receives user input and sends the appropriate messages to its underlying Views.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] This design also includes an Editor as a specialized kind of controller used to modify a particular view, and which is created through that view.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] Smalltalk-80 supports a version of MVC that evolved from this one.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] It provides abstract `view` and `controller` classes as well as various concrete subclasses of each that represent different generic widgets.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] In this scheme, a `View` represents some way of displaying information to the user, and a `controller` represents some way for the user to interact with a `view`.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] A `view` is also coupled to a model object, but the structure of that object is left up to the application programmer.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] The Smalltalk-80 environment also includes an "MVC Inspector", a development tool for viewing the structure of a given model, view, and controller side-by-side.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] In 1988, an article in *The Journal of Object Technology* (JOT) by two ex-PARC employees presented MVC as a general "programming paradigm and methodology" for Smalltalk-80 developers.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] However, their scheme differed from both Reenskaug et al.'s and that presented by the Smalltalk-80 reference books.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] They defined a view as covering any graphical concern, with a controller being a more abstract, generally invisible object that receives user input and interacts with one or many views and only one model.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] The MVC pattern subsequently evolved, giving rise to variants such as hierarchical model–view–controller (HMVC), model–view–adapter (MVA), model–view–presenter (MVP), model–view–viewmodel (MVVM), and others that adapted MVC to different contexts.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] The use of the MVC pattern in web applications grew after the introduction of NeXT's WebObjects in 1996, which was originally written in Objective-C (that borrowed heavily from Smalltalk) and helped enforce MVC principles.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] Later, the MVC pattern became popular with Java developers when WebObjects was ported to Java.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] Later frameworks for Java, such as Spring (released in October 2002), continued the strong bond between Java and MVC.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] This is close to the approach taken by the Ruby on Rails web application framework (August 2004), which has the client send requests to the server via an in-browser view, these requests are handled by a controller on the server, and the controller communicates with the appropriate model objects.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] The Django framework (July 2005, for Python) put forward a similar "model-template-view" (MTV) take on the pattern, in which a view retrieves data from models and passes it to templates for display.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] Both Rails and Django debuted with a strong emphasis on rapid deployment, which increased MVC's popularity outside the traditional enterprise environment in which it has long been popular.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] It is the application's dynamic data structure, independent of the user interface.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] It directly manages the data, logic and rules of the application.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] In Smalltalk-80, the design of a model type is left entirely to the programmer.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] With WebObjects, Rails, and Django, a model type typically represents a table in the application's database.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] The model is essential for keeping the data organized and consistent.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] It ensures that the application's data behaves according to the defined rules and logic.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] Any representation of information such as a chart, diagram or table.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] Multiple views of the same information are possible, such as a bar chart for management and a tabular view for accountants.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] In Smalltalk-80, a view is just a visual representation of a model, and does not handle user input.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] With WebObjects, a view represents a complete user interface element such as a menu or button, and does receive input from the user.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] In both Smalltalk-80 and WebObjects, however, views are meant to be general-purpose and composable.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] With Rails and Django, the role of the view is played by HTML templates, so in their scheme a view specifies an in-browser user interface rather than representing a user interface widget directly.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] (Django opts to call this kind of object a "template" in light of this.) This approach puts relatively less emphasis on small, composable views; a typical Rails view has a one-to-one relationship with a controller action.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] Smalltalk-80 views communicate with both a model and a controller, whereas with WebObjects, a view talks only to a controller, which then talks to a model.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] With Rails and Django, a view/template is used by a controller/view when preparing a response to the client.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] Accepts input and converts it to commands for the model or view.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] A Smalltalk-80 controller handles user input events, such as button presses or mouse movement.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] At any given time, each controller has one associated view and model, although one model object may hear from many different controllers.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] Only one controller, the "active" controller, receives user input at any given time; a global window manager object is responsible for setting the current active controller.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] If user input prompts a change in a model, the controller will signal the model to change, but the model is then responsible for telling its views to update.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] In WebObjects, the views handle user input, and the controller mediates between the views and the models.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] There may be only one controller per application, or one controller per window.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] Much of the application-specific logic is found in the controller.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] In Rails, requests arriving at the on-server application from the client are sent to a "router", which maps the request to a specific method of a specific controller.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] Within that method, the controller interacts with the request data and any relevant model objects and prepares a response using a view.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] Conventionally, each view has an associated controller; for example, if the application had a `client` view, it would typically have an associated `Clients` controller as well.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] However, developers are free to make other kinds of controllers if they wish.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] Django calls the object playing this role a "view" instead of a controller.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] A Django view is a function that receives a web request and returns a web response.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] It may use templates to create the response.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] As with other software patterns, MVC expresses the "core of the solution" to a problem while allowing it to be adapted for each system.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] Particular MVC designs can vary significantly from the traditional description here.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] As Alan Kay wrote in 2003, the original motivation behind the MVC was to allow creation of a graphical interface for any object.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] That was outlined in detail in Richard Pawson's book *Naked Objects*.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] Although originally developed for desktop computing, MVC has been widely adopted as a design for World Wide Web applications in major programming languages.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] Several web frameworks have been created that enforce the pattern.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] These software frameworks vary in their interpretations, mainly in the way that the MVC responsibilities are divided between the client and server.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] Early MVC frameworks took a thin client approach that placed almost the entire model, view and controller logic on the server.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] In this approach, the client sends hyperlink requests or form submissions to the controller and then receives a complete and updated web page (or other document) from the view; the model exists entirely on the server.
[src:rails-deep/model-view-controller] Later frameworks have allowed the MVC components to execute partly on the client, using Ajax to synchronize data.
[src:rails-deep/object-relational-mapping] In object-oriented programming, data-management tasks act on objects that combine scalar values into objects.
[src:rails-deep/object-relational-mapping] For example, consider an address book entry that represents a single person along with zero or more phone numbers and zero or more addresses.
[src:rails-deep/object-relational-mapping] This could be modeled in an object-oriented implementation by a "Person object" with an attribute/field to hold each data item that the entry comprises: the person's name, a list of phone numbers, and a list of addresses.
[src:rails-deep/object-relational-mapping] The list of phone numbers would itself contain "PhoneNumber objects" and so on.
[src:rails-deep/object-relational-mapping] Each such address-book entry is treated as a single object by the programming language (it can be referenced by a single variable containing a pointer to the object, for instance).
[src:rails-deep/object-relational-mapping] Various methods can be associated with the object, such as methods to return the preferred phone number, the home address, and so on.
[src:rails-deep/object-relational-mapping] By contrast, relational databases, such as SQL, group scalars into tuples, which are then enumerated in tables.
[src:rails-deep/object-relational-mapping] Tuples and objects have some general similarity, in that they are both ways to collect values into named fields such that the whole collection can be manipulated as a single compound entity.
[src:rails-deep/object-relational-mapping] They have many differences, though, in particular: lifecycle management (row insertion and deletion, versus garbage collection or reference counting), references to other entities (object references, versus foreign key references), and inheritance (non-existent in relational databases).
[src:rails-deep/object-relational-mapping] As well, objects are managed on-heap and are under full control of a single process, while database tuples are shared and must incorporate locking, merging, and retry.
[src:rails-deep/object-relational-mapping] Object–relational mapping provides automated support for mapping tuples to objects and back, while accounting for all of these differences.
[src:rails-deep/object-relational-mapping] The heart of the problem involves translating the logical representation of the objects into an atomized form that is capable of being stored in the database while preserving the properties of the objects and their relationships so that they can be reloaded as objects when needed.
[src:rails-deep/object-relational-mapping] If this storage and retrieval functionality is implemented, the objects are said to be persistent.
[src:rails-deep/object-relational-mapping] Implementation-specific details of storage drivers are generally wrapped in an API in the programming language in use, exposing methods to interact with the storage medium in a way which is simpler and more in line with the paradigms of surrounding code.
[src:rails-deep/object-relational-mapping] The following is a simple example, written in C# code, to execute a query written in SQL using a database engine.
[src:rails-deep/object-relational-mapping] In contrast, the following makes use of an ORM-job API which makes it possible to write code that naturally makes use of the features of the language.
[src:rails-deep/object-relational-mapping] The case above makes use of an object representing the storage repository and methods of that object.
[src:rails-deep/object-relational-mapping] Other frameworks might provide code as static methods, as in the example below, and yet other methods may not implement an object-oriented system at all.
[src:rails-deep/object-relational-mapping] Often the choice of paradigm is made for the best fit of the ORM into the surrounding language's design principles.
[src:rails-deep/object-relational-mapping] Compared to traditional techniques of exchange between an object-oriented language and a relational database, ORM often reduces the amount of code that needs to be written.
[src:rails-deep/object-relational-mapping] Disadvantages of ORM tools generally stem from the high level of abstraction obscuring what is actually happening in the implementation code.
[src:rails-deep/object-relational-mapping] Another approach is to use an object-oriented database management system (OODBMS) or document-oriented databases such as native XML databases that provide more flexibility in data modeling.
[src:rails-deep/object-relational-mapping] OODBMSs are databases designed specifically for working with object-oriented values.
[src:rails-deep/object-relational-mapping] Using an OODBMS eliminates the need for converting data to and from its SQL form, as the data is stored in its original object representation and relationships are directly represented, rather than requiring join tables/operations.
[src:rails-deep/object-relational-mapping] The equivalent of ORMs for document-oriented databases are called object-document mappers (ODMs).
[src:rails-deep/object-relational-mapping] Document-oriented databases also prevent the user from having to "shred" objects into table rows.
[src:rails-deep/object-relational-mapping] Many of these systems also support the XQuery query language to retrieve datasets.
[src:rails-deep/object-relational-mapping] Object-oriented databases tend to be used in complex, niche applications.
[src:rails-deep/object-relational-mapping] One of the arguments against using an OODBMS is that it may not be able to execute ad-hoc, application-independent queries.
[src:rails-deep/object-relational-mapping] For this reason, many programmers find themselves more at home with an object-SQL mapping system, even though most object-oriented databases are able to process SQL queries to a limited extent.
[src:rails-deep/object-relational-mapping] Other OODBMS provide replication to SQL databases, as a means of addressing the need for ad-hoc queries, while preserving well-known query patterns.
[src:rails-deep/object-relational-mapping] A variety of difficulties arise when considering how to match an object system to a relational database.
[src:rails-deep/object-relational-mapping] These difficulties are referred to as the object–relational impedance mismatch.
[src:rails-deep/object-relational-mapping] An alternative to implementing ORM is use of the native procedural languages provided with every major database.
[src:rails-deep/object-relational-mapping] These can be called from the client using SQL statements.
[src:rails-deep/object-relational-mapping] The Data Access Object (DAO) design pattern is used to abstract these statements and offer a lightweight object-oriented interface to the rest of the application.
[src:rails-deep/object-relational-mapping] ORMs are limited to their predefined functionality, which may not cover all edge cases or database features.
[src:rails-deep/object-relational-mapping] They usually mitigate this limitation by providing users with an interface to write raw queries, such as Django ORM.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] Ruby on Rails' emergence in 2005 greatly influenced web app development, through innovative features such as seamless database table creations, migrations, and scaffolding of views to enable rapid application development.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] Ruby on Rails' influence on other web frameworks remains apparent today, with many frameworks in other languages borrowing its ideas, including Django in Python; Catalyst in Perl; Laravel, CakePHP and Yii in PHP; Grails in Groovy; Phoenix in Elixir; Play in Scala; and Sails.js in Node.js.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] Well-known sites that use Ruby on Rails include Airbnb, Archive of Our Own, Crunchbase, Dribbble, GitHub, Twitch and Shopify.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] David Heinemeier Hansson extracted Ruby on Rails from his work on the project management tool Basecamp at the web application company 37signals.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] Hansson first released Rails as open source in July 2004, but did not share commit rights to the project until February 2005.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] In August 2006, the framework reached a milestone when Apple announced that it would ship Ruby on Rails with Mac OS X v10.5 "Leopard", which was released in October 2007.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] Rails version 2.3 was released on 15 March 2009, with major new developments in templates, engines, Rack and nested model forms.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] Templates enable the developer to generate a skeleton application with custom gems and configurations.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] Engines give developers the ability to reuse application pieces complete with routes, view paths and models.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] The Rack web server interface and Metal allow one to write optimized pieces of code that route around Action Controller.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] On 23 December 2008, Merb, another web application framework, was launched, and Ruby on Rails announced it would work with the Merb project to bring "the best ideas of Merb" into Rails 3, ending the "unnecessary duplication" across both communities.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] Merb was merged with Rails as part of the Rails 3.0 release.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] Rails 3.1 was released on 31 August 2011, featuring Reversible Database Migrations, Asset Pipeline, Streaming, jQuery as default JavaScript library and newly introduced CoffeeScript and Sass into the stack.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] Rails 3.2 was released on 20 January 2012 with a faster development mode and routing engine (also known as Journey engine), Automatic Query Explain and Tagged Logging.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] Rails 3.2.x is the last version that supports Ruby 1.8.7.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] Rails 4.0 was released on 25 June 2013, introducing Russian Doll Caching, Turbolinks, and Live Streaming as well as making Active Resource, Active Record Observer and other components optional by splitting them as gems.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] Rails 4.1 was released on 8 April 2014, introducing Spring, Variants, Enums, Mailer previews, and secrets.yml.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] Rails 4.2 was released on 19 December 2014, introducing Active Job, asynchronous emails, Adequate Record, Web Console, and foreign keys.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] Rails 5.0 was released on 30 June 2016, introducing Action Cable, API mode, and Turbolinks 5.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] Rails 5.0.0.1 was released on 10 August 2016, with Exclusive use of rails CLI over Rake and support for Ruby version 2.2.2 and above.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] Rails 5.2 was released on 9 April 2018, introducing new features that include ActiveStorage, built-in Redis Cache Store, updated Rails Credentials and a new DSL that allows for configuring a Content Security Policy for an application.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] Rails 5.2.2 was released on 4 December 2018, introducing numerous bug fixes and several logic improvements.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] Rails 6.0 was released on 16 August 2019, making Webpack default, adding mailbox routing, a default online rich-text editor, parallel testing, multiple database support, mailer routing and a new autoloader.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] Rails 7.0 was released on 15 December 2021, replacing Node.js and Webpack with import maps for JavaScript management by default, replacing Turbolinks with a combination of Turbo and Stimulus, adding at-work encryption into Active Record, using Zeitwerk exclusively for code loading, and more.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] Rails 7.1 was released on 5 October 2023, Dockerfiles support using Kamal in order to deploy your application, authentication improvements, and now including support for Bun.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] Ruby on Rails 8.0.0 was released on 8 November 2024.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] This major release introduces fundamental shifts in Rails development, enabling individual developers to host and manage their applications independently without the need for a Platform-as-a-service.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] The update focuses on empowering single developers to handle all aspects of application deployment and management seamlessly.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] Ruby on Rails 8.1.0 was released on October 24, 2025.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] Major features include Active Job Continuations, Structured Event Reporting, Local CI, and Markdown rendering.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] A revised maintenance policy was instituted in October 2024.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] Ruby on Rails evolves radically from release to release exploring the use of new technologies and adopting new standards on the Internet.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] Some features are very stable in Ruby on Rails while some are replaced in favour of new techniques.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] The model–view–controller (MVC) pattern is the fundamental structure to organize application programming.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] In a default configuration, a *model* in the Ruby on Rails framework maps to a table in a database and to a Ruby file.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] For example, a model class *User* will usually be defined in the file 'user.rb' in the app/models directory, and linked to the table 'users' in the database.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] While developers are free to ignore this convention and choose differing names for their models, files, and database table, this is not common practice and is usually discouraged in accordance with the "convention-over-configuration" philosophy.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] A *controller* is a server-side component of Rails that responds to external requests from the web server to the application, by determining which view file to render.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] The controller may also have to query one or more models for information and pass these on to the view.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] For example, in an airline reservation system, a controller implementing a flight-search function would need to query a model representing individual flights to find flights matching the search, and might also need to query models representing airports and airlines to find related secondary data.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] The controller might then pass some subset of the flight data to the corresponding view, which would contain a mixture of static HTML and logic that use the flight data to create an HTML document containing a table with one row per flight.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] A controller may provide one or more actions.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] In Ruby on Rails, an action is typically a basic unit that describes how to respond to a specific external web-browser request.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] Also, note that the controller/action will be accessible for external web requests only if a corresponding route is mapped to it.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] Rails encourages developers to use RESTful routes, which include actions such as create, new, edit, update, destroy, show, and index.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] These mappings of incoming requests/routes to controller actions can be easily set up in the routes.rb configuration file.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] A *view* in the default configuration of Rails is an erb file, which is evaluated and converted to HTML at run-time.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] Alternatively, many other templating systems can be used for views.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] Ruby on Rails includes tools that make common development tasks easier "out-of-the-box", such as scaffolding that can automatically construct some of the models and views needed for a basic website.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] Also included are WEBrick, a simple Ruby web server that is distributed with Ruby, and Rake, a build system, distributed as a gem.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] Together with Ruby on Rails, these tools provide a basic development environment.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] Ruby on Rails is most commonly not connected to the Internet directly, but through some front-end web server.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] Mongrel was generally preferred over WEBrick in the early days, but it can also run on Lighttpd, Apache, Cherokee, Hiawatha, Nginx (either as a module – Phusion Passenger for example – or via CGI, FastCGI or mod ruby), and many others.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] From 2008 onward, Passenger replaced Mongrel as the most-used web server for Ruby on Rails.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] Ruby is also supported natively on IBM i.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] Ruby on Rails is also noteworthy for its extensive use of the JavaScript libraries Prototype and Script.aculo.us for scripting Ajax actions.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] Ruby on Rails 3.0 separates the markup of the page (which defines the structure of the page) from scripting (which determines functionality or logic of the page).
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] As of version 7.0, new Ruby on Rails applications come with the Hotwire family of JavaScript libraries installed by default.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] Since version 2.0, Ruby on Rails offers both HTML and XML as standard output formats.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] The latter is the facility for RESTful web services.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] Rails 3.1 introduced Sass as standard CSS templating.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] By default, the server uses Embedded Ruby in the HTML views, with files having an html.erb extension.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] Rails supports swapping-in alternative templating languages, such as HAML and Mustache.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] Ruby on Rails 3.0 has been designed to work with Ruby 1.8.7, Ruby 1.9.2, and JRuby 1.5.2+; earlier versions are not supported.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] Ruby on Rails 3.2 is the last series of releases that support Ruby 1.8.7.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] Ruby on Rails is separated into various packages, namely ActiveRecord (an object-relational mapping system for database access), Action Pack, Active Support and Action Mailer.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] Prior to version 2.0, Ruby on Rails also included the Action Web Service package that is now replaced by Active Resource.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] Apart from standard packages, developers can make plugins to extend existing packages.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] Earlier Rails supported plugins within their own custom framework; version 3.2 deprecates these in favor of standard Ruby "gems".
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] Ruby on Rails is often installed using RubyGems, a package manager which is included with current versions of Ruby.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] Many free Unix-like systems also support installation of Ruby on Rails and its dependencies through their native package management system.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] Ruby on Rails is typically deployed with a database server such as MySQL or PostgreSQL, and a web server such as Apache running the Phusion Passenger module.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] Ruby on Rails is intended to emphasize *Convention over Configuration* (CoC), and the *Don't Repeat Yourself* (DRY) principle.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] The Rails Doctrine is an enduring enabler that guides the philosophy, design, and implementation of the Ruby on Rails framework.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] "Convention over Configuration" means a developer only needs to specify unconventional aspects of the application.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] For example, if there is a class *Sale* in the model, the corresponding table in the database is called *sales* by default.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] It is only if one deviates from this convention, such as calling the table "products sold", that the developer needs to write code regarding these names.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] Generally, Ruby on Rails conventions lead to less code and less repetition.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] "Don't repeat yourself" means that information is located in a single, unambiguous place.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] For example, using the ActiveRecord module of Rails, the developer does not need to specify database column names in class definitions.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] Instead, Ruby on Rails can retrieve this information from the database based on the class name.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] "Fat models, skinny controllers" means that most of the application logic should be placed within the model while leaving the controller as light as possible.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] HTML Over The Wire (Hotwire), Conceptual compression, and robust security mark Rails 7.0's approach to the One person framework.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] In March 2007, David Heinemeier Hansson applied to register three Ruby on Rails-related trademarks with the USPTO.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] These applications concern the phrase "RUBY ON RAILS", the word "RAILS", and the official Rails logo.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] In the summer of 2007, Hansson denied the publisher Apress permission to use the Ruby on Rails logo on the cover of a new Ruby on Rails book written by some authoritative community members.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] The episode gave rise to a polite protest in the Ruby on Rails community.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] The trademark of the logo was cancelled on 25 October 2019.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] In earlier days, Rails running on Matz's Ruby Interpreter (the *de facto* reference interpreter for Ruby) had been criticized for issues with scalability.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] These critiques often mentioned various Twitter outages in 2007 and 2008, which spurred Twitter's partial transition to Scala (which runs on the Java Virtual Machine) for their queueing system and other middleware.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] The user interface aspects of the site continued to run Ruby on Rails until 2011 when it was replaced due to concerns over performance.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] On the other hand, many Rails business application developers relied on system architecture design, including choices of database engine, cache configuration, and servers, to tackle scalability issues.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] The original author of Rails, David Heinemeier Hansson, criticized Twitter, saying that their problems scaling were the consequences of their own poor architectural decisions and not the fault of Rails.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] According to Hansson, blaming Rails for their troubles while making no contributions to the framework is ungrateful and unjust.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] In 2011, Gartner Research noted that despite criticisms and comparisons to Java, many high-profile consumer web firms are using Ruby on Rails to build scalable web applications.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] Some of the largest sites running Ruby on Rails include Airbnb, Cookpad, GitHub, GitLab, Scribd, Shopify, and Basecamp.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] As of January 2016, it is estimated that more than 1.2 million web sites are running Ruby on Rails.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] In March 2012, security researcher Egor Homakov discovered a mass assignment vulnerability that allowed certain Rails applications to be remotely exploited, and demonstrated it by non-maliciously hacking GitHub after his earlier attempts at responsible disclosure were dismissed.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] On 24 September 2013, a session cookie persistence security flaw was reported in Ruby on Rails.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] In a default configuration, the entire session hash is stored within a session cookie known as *CookieStore*, allowing any authenticated session possessing the session cookie to log in as the target user at any time in the future.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] As a workaround, administrators are advised to configure cookies to be stored on the server using mechanisms such as *ActiveRecordStore*.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] Researchers Daniel Jackson and Joseph Near developed a data debugger they called "Space" that can analyze the data access of a Rails program and determine if the program properly adheres to rules regarding access restrictions.
[src:rails-deep/ruby-on-rails] On 15 April 2016, Near reported that an analysis of 50 popular Web applications using Space uncovered 23 previously unknown security flaws.
[src:rails-deep/web-service] In a web service, a web technology such as HTTP is used for transferring machine-readable file formats such as XML and JSON.
[src:rails-deep/web-service] In practice, a web service commonly provides an object-oriented web-based interface to a database server, utilized for example by another web server, or by a mobile app, that provides a user interface to the end-user.
[src:rails-deep/web-service] Many organizations that provide data in formatted HTML pages will also provide that data on their server as XML or JSON, often through a Web service to allow syndication.
[src:rails-deep/web-service] Another application offered to the end-user may be a mashup, where a Web server consumes several Web services at different machines and compiles the content into one user interface.
[src:rails-deep/web-service] Asynchronous JavaScript and XML (AJAX) is a dominant technology for Web services.
[src:rails-deep/web-service] Developing from the combination of HTTP servers, JavaScript clients and Plain Old XML (as distinct from SOAP and W3C Web Services), now it is frequently used with JSON as well as, or instead of, XML.
[src:rails-deep/web-service] Representational State Transfer (REST) is an architecture for well-behaved Web services that can function at Internet scale.
[src:rails-deep/web-service] A Web API is a development in Web services where emphasis has been moving to simpler representational state transfer (REST) based communications.
[src:rails-deep/web-service] Restful APIs do not require XML-based Web service protocols (SOAP and WSDL) to support their interfaces.
[src:rails-deep/web-service] W3C Web Services may use SOAP over HTTP protocol, allowing less costly (more efficient) interactions over the Internet than via proprietary solutions like EDI/B2B.
[src:rails-deep/web-service] Besides SOAP over HTTP, Web services can also be implemented on other reliable transport mechanisms like FTP.
[src:rails-deep/web-service] The term "Web service" describes a standardized way of integrating Web-based applications using the XML, SOAP, WSDL and UDDI open standards over an Internet Protocol backbone.
[src:rails-deep/web-service] XML is the data format used to contain the data and provide metadata around it, SOAP is used to transfer the data, WSDL is used for describing the services available and UDDI lists what services are available.
[src:rails-deep/web-service] A Web service is a method of communication between two electronic devices over a network.
[src:rails-deep/web-service] It is a software function provided at a network address over the Web with the service *always-on* as in the concept of utility computing.
[src:rails-deep/web-service] Many organizations use multiple software systems for management.
[src:rails-deep/web-service] Different software systems often need to exchange data with each other, and a Web service is a method of communication that allows two software systems to exchange this data over the Internet.
[src:rails-deep/web-service] The software system that requests data is called a *service requester*, whereas the software system that would process the request and provide the data is called a *service provider*.
[src:rails-deep/web-service] Different software may use different programming languages, and hence there is a need for a method of data exchange that doesn't depend upon a particular programming language.
[src:rails-deep/web-service] Most types of software can, however, interpret XML tags.
[src:rails-deep/web-service] Thus, Web services can use XML files for data exchange.
[src:rails-deep/web-service] All of these rules for communication are defined in a file called WSDL (Web Services Description Language), which has a `.wsdl` extension.
[src:rails-deep/web-service] A directory called UDDI (Universal Description, Discovery, and Integration) defines which software system should be contacted for which type of data.
[src:rails-deep/web-service] So when one software system needs one particular report/data, it would go to the UDDI and find out which other systems it can contact for receiving that data.
[src:rails-deep/web-service] Once the software system finds out which other systems it should contact, it would then contact that system using a special protocol called SOAP (Simple Object Access Protocol).
[src:rails-deep/web-service] The service provider system would first validate the data request by referring to the WSDL file, and then process the request and send the data under the SOAP protocol.
[src:rails-deep/web-service] Automated tools can aid in the creation of a Web service.
[src:rails-deep/web-service] For services using WSDL, it is possible to either automatically generate WSDL for existing classes (a bottom-up model) or to generate a class skeleton given existing WSDL (a top-down model).
[src:rails-deep/web-service] Critics of non-RESTful Web services often complain that they are too complex and based upon large software vendors or integrators, rather than typical open source implementations.
[src:rails-deep/web-service] There are also concerns about performance due to Web services' use of XML as a message format and SOAP/HTTP in enveloping and transporting.
[src:rails-deep/web-service] Functional and non-functional testing of Web services is done with the help of WSDL parsing.
[src:rails-deep/web-service] Regression testing is performed by identifying the changes made to upgrade software.
[src:rails-deep/web-service] Web service regression testing needs can be categorized in three different ways, namely, changes in WSDL, changes in the code, and selective re-testing of operations.
[src:rails-deep/web-service] We can capture the above three needs in three intermediate forms of Subset WSDL, namely, Difference WSDL (DWSDL), Unit WSDL (UWSDL), and Reduced WSDL (RWSDL), respectively.
[src:rails-deep/web-service] These three Subset WSDLs are then combined to form Combined WSDL (CWSDL) that is further used for regression testing of the Web service.
[src:rails-deep/web-service] This will help in Automated Web Service Change Management (AWSCM), by performing the selection of the relevant test cases to construct a reduced test suite from the old test suite.
[src:rails-deep/web-service] Web services testing can also be automated using several test automation tools like SoapUI, Oracle Application Testing Suite (OATS), Unified Functional Testing, Selenium, etc.
[src:rails-deep/web-service] Work-related to the capture and visualization of changes made to a Web service.
[src:rails-deep/web-service] Visualization and computation of changes can be done in the form of intermediate artifacts (Subset WSDL).
[src:rails-deep/web-service] The insight on the computation of change impact is helpful in testing, top-down development and reduce regression testing.
[src:rails-deep/web-service] AWSCM is a tool that can identify subset operations in a WSDL file to construct a subset WSDL.
[src:rails-deep/web-service] While UDDI was intended to serve as a service directory and become the means to discovering web services, many vendors discontinued their UDDI solutions or repositories between 2005 and 2008, including Microsoft, SAP, IBM, among others.
[src:rails-deep/web-service] A key study published in WWW2008 Conference (Beijing, China) presented the state of SOAP-based web services and concluded that only 63% of the available SOAP-based web services at the time of the study were actually active or can be invoked.
[src:rails-deep/web-service] The study also found that search engines were becoming an ideal source for searching for web services compared to that of service registries like the UDDI due its design complexity.
